# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: function-calling-llm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:function-calling-llm/application-programming-interface] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In computer programming, a **function** (also **procedure**, **method**, **subroutine**, **routine**, or **subprogram**) is a **callable unit** of software logic that has a well-formed interface and behavior and can be invoked multiple times.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Callable units provide a powerful programming tool.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The primary purpose is to allow for the decomposition of a large and/or complicated problem into chunks that have relatively low cognitive load and to assign the chunks meaningful names (unless they are anonymous).
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Judicious application can reduce the cost of developing and maintaining software, while increasing its quality and reliability.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Callable units are present at multiple levels of abstraction in the programming environment.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For example, a programmer may write a function in source code that is compiled to machine code that implements similar semantics.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] There is a callable unit in the source code and an associated one in the machine code, but they are different kinds of callable units – with different implications and features.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some object-oriented languages, such as Java and C#, refer to functions inside classes as "methods".
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] However, Alan Turing had discussed subroutines in a paper of 1945 on design proposals for the NPL ACE, going so far as to invent the concept of a return address stack.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The idea of a subroutine was worked out after computing machines had already existed for some time.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The arithmetic and conditional jump instructions were planned ahead of time and have changed relatively little, but the special instructions used for procedure calls have changed greatly over the years.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The earliest computers, such as the Manchester Baby, and some early microprocessors, such as the RCA 1802, did not have a single subroutine call instruction.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Subroutines could be implemented, but they required programmers to use the call sequence—a series of instructions—at each call site.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A single subroutine was implemented in 1945 in Konrad Zuse's Z4 in the form of a tape.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In 1945, Alan Turing used the terms "bury" and "unbury" as a means of calling and returning from subroutines.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In January 1947 John Mauchly presented general notes at *A Symposium of Large Scale Digital Calculating Machinery* under the joint sponsorship of Harvard University and the Bureau of Ordnance, United States Navy.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Kay McNulty had worked closely with John Mauchly on the ENIAC team and developed an idea for subroutines for the ENIAC computer she was programming during World War II.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] She and the other ENIAC programmers used the subroutines to help calculate missile trajectories.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Goldstine and von Neumann wrote a paper dated 16 August 1948 discussing the use of subroutines.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Machines before the mid-1960s, such as the UNIVAC I, the PDP-1, and the IBM 1130, typically use a calling convention which saved the instruction counter in the first memory location of the called subroutine.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This allows arbitrarily deep levels of subroutine nesting but does not support recursive subroutines.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The IBM System/360 had a subroutine call instruction that placed the saved instruction counter value into a general-purpose register; with additional code, this can be used to support arbitrarily deep subroutine nesting and recursive subroutines.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The Burroughs B5000 (1961) is one of the first computers to store subroutine return data on a stack.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The DEC PDP-6 (1964) is one of the first accumulator-based machines to have a subroutine call instruction that saved the return address in a stack addressed by an accumulator or index register.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The later PDP-10 (1966), PDP-11 (1970) and VAX-11 (1976) lines followed suit; this feature also supports both arbitrarily deep subroutine nesting and recursive subroutines.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In the very early assemblers, subroutine support was limited.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Subroutines were not explicitly separated from each other or from the main program, and indeed the source code of a subroutine could be interspersed with that of other subprograms.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some assemblers would offer predefined macros to generate the call and return sequences.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] By the 1960s, assemblers usually had much more sophisticated support for both inline and separately assembled subroutines that could be linked together.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] One of the first programming languages to support user-written subroutines and functions was FORTRAN II.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The IBM FORTRAN II compiler was released in 1958.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] ALGOL 58 and other early programming languages also supported procedural programming.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Even with this cumbersome approach, subroutines proved very useful.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] They allowed the use of the same code in many different programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Memory was a very scarce resource on early computers, and subroutines allowed significant savings in the size of programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Many early computers loaded the program instructions into memory from a punched paper tape.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Each subroutine could then be provided by a separate piece of tape, loaded or spliced before or after the main program (or "mainline"); and the same subroutine tape could then be used by many different programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A similar approach was used in computers that loaded program instructions from punched cards.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The name *subroutine library* originally meant a library, in the literal sense, which kept indexed collections of tapes or decks of cards for collective use.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] To remove the need for self-modifying code, computer designers eventually provided an *indirect jump* instruction, whose operand, instead of being the return address itself, was the location of a variable or processor register containing the return address.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] On those computers, instead of modifying the function's return jump, the calling program would store the return address in a variable so that when the function completed, it would execute an indirect jump that would direct execution to the location given by the predefined variable.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Another advance was the *jump to subroutine* instruction, which combined the saving of the return address with the calling jump, thereby minimizing overhead significantly.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] At least five forms of this existed in the 1950s.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The IBM System/360 architecture is an example of saving the return address into a designated register.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The branch instructions BAL or BALR, designed for procedure calling, would save the return address in a processor register specified in the instruction, by convention register 14.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] To return, the subroutine had only to execute an indirect branch instruction (BR) through that register.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If the subroutine needed that register for some other purpose (such as calling another subroutine), it would save the register's contents to a private memory location or a register stack.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The HP 2100 architecture is an example of saving the return address in the first word of the subroutine.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The JSB instruction would save the return address in the memory location that was the target of the branch.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Execution of the procedure would begin at the next memory location.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] to call a subroutine called MYSUB from the main program.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The JSB instruction placed the address of the NEXT instruction (namely, BB) into the location specified as its operand (namely, MYSUB), and then branched to the NEXT location after that (namely, AA = MYSUB + 1).
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The subroutine could then return to the main program by executing the indirect jump JMP MYSUB, I which branched to the location stored at location MYSUB.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Compilers for Fortran and other languages could easily make use of these instructions when available.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This approach supported multiple levels of calls; however, since the return address, parameters, and return values of a subroutine were assigned fixed memory locations, it did not allow for recursive calls.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Incidentally, a similar method was used by Lotus 1-2-3, in the early 1980s, to discover the recalculation dependencies in a spreadsheet.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Namely, a location was reserved in each cell to store the *return* address.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Since circular references are not allowed for natural recalculation order, this allows a tree walk without reserving space for a stack in memory, which was very limited on small computers such as the IBM PC.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Most modern implementations of a function call use a call stack, a special case of the stack data structure, to implement function calls and returns.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Each procedure call creates a new entry, called a *stack frame*, at the top of the stack; when the procedure returns, its stack frame is deleted from the stack, and its space may be used for other procedure calls.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Each stack frame contains the *private data* of the corresponding call, which typically includes the procedure's parameters and internal variables, and the return address.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The call stack is usually implemented as a contiguous area of memory.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] It is an arbitrary design choice whether the bottom of the stack is the lowest or highest address within this area, so that the stack may grow forwards or backwards in memory; however, many architectures chose the latter.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some designs, notably some Forth implementations, used two separate stacks, one mainly for control information (like return addresses and loop counters) and the other for data.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The former was, or worked like, a call stack and was only indirectly accessible to the programmer through other language constructs while the latter was more directly accessible.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] When stack-based procedure calls were first introduced, an important motivation was to save precious memory.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] With this scheme, the compiler does not have to reserve separate space in memory for the private data (parameters, return address, and local variables) of each procedure.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] At any moment, the stack contains only the private data of the calls that are currently *active* (namely, which have been called but haven't returned yet).
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Because of the ways in which programs were usually assembled from libraries, it was (and still is) not uncommon to find programs that include thousands of functions, of which only a handful are active at any given moment.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For such programs, the call stack mechanism could save significant amounts of memory.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Indeed, the call stack mechanism can be viewed as the earliest and simplest method for automatic memory management.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] However, another advantage of the call stack method is that it allows recursive function calls, since each nested call to the same procedure gets a separate instance of its private data.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In a multi-threaded environment, there is generally more than one stack.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] An environment that fully supports coroutines or lazy evaluation may use data structures other than stacks to store their activation records.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] One disadvantage of the call stack mechanism is the increased cost of a procedure call and its matching return.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The extra cost includes incrementing and decrementing the stack pointer (and, in some architectures, checking for stack overflow), and accessing the local variables and parameters by frame-relative addresses, instead of absolute addresses.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The cost may be realized in increased execution time, or increased processor complexity, or both.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This overhead is most obvious and objectionable in *leaf procedures* or *leaf functions*, which return without making any procedure calls themselves.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] To reduce that overhead, many modern compilers try to delay the use of a call stack until it is really needed.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For example, the call of a procedure *P* may store the return address and parameters of the called procedure in certain processor registers, and transfer control to the procedure's body by a simple jump.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If the procedure *P* returns without making any other call, the call stack is not used at all.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If *P* needs to call another procedure *Q*, it will then use the call stack to save the contents of any registers (such as the return address) that will be needed after *Q* returns.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In general, a callable unit is a list of instructions that, starting at the first instruction, executes sequentially except as directed via its internal logic.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] It can be invoked (called) many times during the execution of a program.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Execution continues at the next instruction after the call instruction when it returns control.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The features of implementations of callable units evolved over time and varies by context.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This section describes features of the various common implementations.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some languages, such as Pascal, Fortran, Ada and many dialects of BASIC, use a different name for a callable unit that returns a value (*function* or *subprogram*) vs. one that does not (*subroutine* or *procedure*).
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Other languages, such as C, C++, C# and Lisp, use only one name for a callable unit, *function*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The C-family languages use the keyword `void` to indicate no return value.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If declared to return a value, a call can be embedded in an expression in order to consume the return value.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For example, a square root callable unit might be called like `y = sqrt(x)`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A callable unit that does not return a value is called as a stand-alone statement like `print("hello")`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This syntax can also be used for a callable unit that returns a value, but the return value will be ignored.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some older languages require a keyword for calls that do not consume a return value, like `CALL print("hello")`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Most implementations, especially in modern languages, support parameters which the callable declares as *formal parameters*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A caller passes *actual parameters*, a.k.a.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Different programming languages provide different conventions for passing arguments.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In some languages, such as BASIC, a callable has different syntax (i.e. keyword) for a callable that returns a value vs. one that does not.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In other languages, the syntax is the same regardless.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In some of these languages an extra keyword is used to declare no return value, such as `void` in C, C++ and C#.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In some languages, such as Python, the difference is whether the body contains a return statement with a value, and a particular callable may return with or without a value based on control flow.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In many contexts, a callable may have side effect behavior such as modifying passed or global data, reading from or writing to a peripheral device, accessing a file, halting the program or the machine, or temporarily pausing program execution.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Side effects are considered undesirable by Robert C.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Martin, who is known for promoting design principles.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Martin argues that side effects can result in temporal coupling or order dependencies.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In strictly functional programming languages such as Haskell, a function can have no side effects, which means it cannot change the state of the program.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Functions always return the same result for the same input.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Such languages typically only support functions that return a value, since there is no value in a function that has neither return value nor side effect.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Most contexts support *local variables* – memory owned by a callable to hold intermediate values.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] These variables are typically stored in the call's *activation record* on the call stack along with other information such as the return address.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If supported by the language, a callable may call itself, causing its execution to suspend while another *nested* execution of the same callable executes.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Recursion is a useful means to simplify some complex algorithms and break down complex problems.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Recursive languages provide a new copy of local variables on each call.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If the programmer desires the recursive callable to use the same variables instead of using locals, they typically declare them in a shared context such static or global.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Languages going back to ALGOL, PL/I and C and modern languages, almost invariably use a call stack, usually supported by the instruction sets to provide an activation record for each call.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] That way, a nested call can modify its local variables without affecting any of the suspended call's variables.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Recursion allows direct implementation of functionality defined by mathematical induction and recursive divide and conquer algorithms.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Early languages like Fortran did not initially support recursion because only one set of variables and return address were allocated for each callable.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Early computer instruction sets made storing return addresses and variables on a stack difficult.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Machines with index registers or general-purpose registers, e.g., CDC 6000 series, PDP-6, GE 635, System/360, UNIVAC 1100 series, could use one of those registers as a stack pointer.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some languages, e.g., Ada, Pascal, PL/I, Python, support declaring and defining a function inside, e.g., a function body, such that the name of the inner is only visible within the body of the outer.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Note that `E`'s parameter `x` is also visible in `F` (as `F` is a part of `E`) while both `x` and `y` are invisible outside `E` and `F` respectively.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If a callable can be executed properly even when another execution of the same callable is already in progress, that callable is said to be *reentrant*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A reentrant callable is also useful in multi-threaded situations since multiple threads can call the same callable without fear of interfering with each other.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In the IBM CICS transaction processing system, *quasi-reentrant* was a slightly less restrictive, but similar, requirement for application programs that were shared by many threads.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some languages support *overloading* – allow multiple callables with the same name in the same scope, but operating on different types of input.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Consider the square root function applied to real number, complex number and matrix input.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The algorithm for each type of input is different, and the return value may have a different type.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] By writing three separate callables with the same name. i.e.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] *sqrt*, the resulting code may be easier to write and to maintain since each one has a name that is relatively easy to understand and to remember instead of giving longer and more complicated names like *sqrt_real*, *sqrt_complex*, *qrt_matrix*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Overloading is supported in many languages that support strong typing.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Often the compiler selects the overload to call based on the type of the input arguments or it fails if the input arguments do not select an overload.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Older and weakly-typed languages generally do not support overloading.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] PL/I has the `GENERIC` attribute to define a generic name for a set of entry references called with different types of arguments.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Multiple argument definitions may be specified for each entry.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A call to "gen_name" will result in a call to "name" when the argument is FIXED BINARY, "flame" when FLOAT", etc.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If the argument matches none of the choices "pathname" will be called.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A *closure* is a callable plus values of some of its variables captured from the environment in which it was created.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Closures were a notable feature of the Lisp programming language, introduced by John McCarthy.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Depending on the implementation, closures can serve as a mechanism for side-effects.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Besides its happy path behavior, a callable may need to inform the caller about an exceptional condition that occurred during its execution.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Most modern languages support exceptions which allows for exceptional control flow that pops the call stack until an exception handler is found to handle the condition.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Languages that do not support exceptions can use the return value to indicate success or failure of a call.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Another approach is to use a well-known location like a global variable for success indication.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A callable writes the value and the caller reads it after a call.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Various techniques are employed to minimize the runtime cost of calls.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some optimizations for minimizing call overhead may seem straight forward, but cannot be used if the callable has side effects.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For example, in the expression `(f(x)-1)/(f(x)+1)`, the function `f` cannot be called only once with its value used two times since the two calls may return different results.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Moreover, in the few languages which define the order of evaluation of the division operator's operands, the value of `x` must be fetched again before the second call, since the first call may have changed it.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Determining whether a callable has a side effect is difficult – indeed, undecidable by virtue of Rice's theorem.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] So, while this optimization is safe in a purely functional programming language, a compiler for a language not limited to functional typically assumes the worst case, that every callable may have side effects.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Inlining eliminates calls for particular callables.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The compiler replaces each call with the compiled code of the callable.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Not only does this avoid the call overhead, but it also allows the compiler to optimize code of the caller more effectively by taking into account the context and arguments at that call.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Inlining, however, usually increases the compiled code size, except when only called once or the body is very short, like one line.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Callables can be defined within a program, or separately in a library that can be used by multiple programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A compiler translates call and return statements into machine instructions according to a well-defined calling convention.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For code compiled by the same or a compatible compiler, functions can be compiled separately from the programs that call them.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The instruction sequences corresponding to call and return statements are called the procedure's prologue and epilogue.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A *built-in function*, or *builtin function*, or *intrinsic function*, is a function for which the compiler generates code at compile time or provides in a way different from other functions.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A built-in function does not need to be defined like other functions since it is *built in* to the programming language.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In some programming languages, for instance C++, Rust and Zig, functions can be evaluated at compile time; reducing the runtime overhead in the ways such as not using additional stack frame, using less memory and baking the return values to the binary code itself.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Compared to using in-line code, invoking a function imposes some computational overhead in the call mechanism.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A function typically requires standard housekeeping code – both at the entry to, and exit from, the function (function prologue and epilogue – usually saving general purpose registers and return address as a minimum).
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Many programming conventions have been developed regarding callables.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] With respect to naming, many developers name a callable with a phrase starting with a verb when it does a certain task, with an adjective when it makes an inquiry, and with a noun when it is used to substitute variables.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Some programmers suggest that a callable should perform exactly one task, and if it performs more than one task, it should be split up into multiple callables.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] They argue that callables are key components in software maintenance, and their roles in the program must remain distinct.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Proponents of modular programming advocate that each callable should have minimal dependency on the rest of the codebase.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For example, the use of global variables is generally deemed unwise, because it adds coupling between all callables that use the global variables.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] If such coupling is not necessary, they advise to refactor callables to accept passed parameters instead.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Early BASIC variants require each line to have a unique number (line number) that orders the lines for execution, provides no separation of the code that is callable, no mechanism for passing arguments or to return a value and all variables are global.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] It provides the command `GOSUB` where *sub* is short for *sub procedure*, *subprocedure* or *subroutine*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Control jumps to the specified line number and then continues on the next line on return.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This code repeatedly asks the user to enter a number and reports the square root of the value.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In Microsoft Small Basic, targeted to the student first learning how to program in a text-based language, a callable unit is called a *subroutine*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The `Sub` keyword denotes the start of a subroutine and is followed by a name identifier.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Subsequent lines are the body which ends with the `EndSub` keyword.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In later versions of Visual Basic (VB), including the latest product line and VB6, the term *procedure* is used for the callable unit concept.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The keyword `Sub` is used to return no value and `Function` to return a value.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] When used in the context of a class, a procedure is a method.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Each parameter has a data type that can be specified, but if not, defaults to `Object` for later versions based on .NET and variant for VB6.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] VB supports parameter passing conventions by value and by reference via the keywords `ByVal` and `ByRef`, respectively.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Unless `ByRef` is specified, an argument is passed `ByVal`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Therefore, `ByVal` is rarely explicitly specified.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For a simple type like a number these conventions are relatively clear.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Passing `ByRef` allows the procedure to modify the passed variable whereas passing `ByVal` does not.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For an object, semantics can confuse programmers since an object is always treated as a reference.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Passing an object `ByVal` copies the reference, not the state of the object.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The called procedure can modify the state of the object via its methods yet cannot modify the object reference of the actual parameter.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This has a side-effect – modifies the variable passed by reference and could be called for variable `v` like `AddTwo(v)`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Giving v is 5 before the call, it will be 7 after.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In C and C++, a callable unit is called a *function*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A function definition starts with the name of the type of value that it returns or `void` to indicate that it does not return a value.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This is followed by the function name, formal arguments in parentheses, and body lines in braces.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In C++, a function declared in a class (as non-static) is called a *member function* or *method*.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A function outside of a class can be called a *free function* to distinguish it from a member function.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This function returns the integer value 5.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This function has a side-effect – modifies the value passed by address to the input value plus 2.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] It could be called for variable `v` as `addTwo(&v)` where the ampersand (&) tells the compiler to pass the address of a variable.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This function requires C++ – would not compile as C.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] It has the same behavior as the preceding example but passes the actual parameter by reference rather than passing its address.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] A call such as `addTwo(v)` does not include an ampersand since the compiler handles passing by reference without syntax in the call.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In PL/I a called procedure may be passed a *descriptor* providing information about the argument, such as string lengths and array bounds.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] This allows the procedure to be more general and eliminates the need for the programmer to pass such information.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] By default PL/I passes arguments by reference.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In Python, the keyword `def` denotes the start of a function definition.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The statements of the function body follow as indented on subsequent lines and end at the line that is indented the same as the first line or end of file.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The first function returns greeting text that includes the name passed by the caller.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] The second function calls the first and is called like `greet_martin()` to write "Welcome Martin" to the console.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] In the procedural interpretation of logic programs, logical implications behave as goal-reduction procedures.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] behaves as a procedure that reduces goals that unify with `A` to subgoals that are instances of`B`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] Notice that the motherhood function, `X = mother(Y)` is represented by a relation, as in a relational database.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] However, *relations* in Prolog *function* as callable units.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] For example, the procedure call `?- parent_child(X, charles)` produces the output `X = elizabeth`.
[src:function-calling-llm/function-computer-programming] But the same procedure can be called with other input-output patterns.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:function-calling-llm/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:function-calling-llm/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:function-calling-llm/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:function-calling-llm/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:function-calling-llm/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:function-calling-llm/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:function-calling-llm/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For large volume scientific datasets, such as satellite data and output of numerical climate, weather, or ocean models, specific binary serialization standards have been developed, e.g.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:function-calling-llm/serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] In computer science, a **software agent** is a computer program that acts for a user or another program in a relationship of agency.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The term *agent* is derived from the Latin *agere* (to do): an agreement to act on one's behalf.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Such "action on behalf of" implies the authority to decide which, if any, action is appropriate.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Some agents are colloquially known as *bots*, from *robot*.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] They may be embodied, as when execution is paired with a robot body, or as software such as a chatbot executing on a computer, such as a mobile device, e.g.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Software agents may be autonomous or work together with other agents or people.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Software agents interacting with people (e.g. chatbots, human-robot interaction environments) may possess human-like qualities such as natural language understanding and speech, personality or embody humanoid form (see Asimo).
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The concept of an agent provides a method of describing a complex software entity that is capable of acting with a certain degree of autonomy in order to accomplish tasks on behalf of its host.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] But unlike objects, which are defined in terms of *methods* and *attributes*, an agent is defined in terms of its behavior.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] All agents are programs, but not all programs are agents.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Contrasting the term with related concepts may help clarify its meaning.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Franklin & Graesser (1997) discuss four key notions that distinguish agents from arbitrary programs: reaction to the environment, autonomy, goal-orientation and persistence.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Software agents may offer various benefits to their end users by automating complex or repetitive tasks.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] However, there are organizational and cultural impacts of this technology that need to be considered prior to implementing software agents.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] People like to perform easy tasks providing the sensation of success unless the repetition of the simple tasking is affecting the overall output.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] In general implementing software agents to perform administrative requirements provides a substantial increase in work contentment, as administering their own work does never please the worker.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The effort freed up serves for a higher degree of engagement in the substantial tasks of individual work.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Hence, software agents may provide the basics to implement self-controlled work, relieved from hierarchical controls and interference.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Such conditions may be secured by application of software agents for required formal support.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The cultural effects of the implementation of software agents include trust affliction, skills erosion, privacy attrition and social detachment.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Some users may not feel entirely comfortable fully delegating important tasks to software applications.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Those who start relying solely on intelligent agents may lose important skills, for example, relating to information literacy.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] In order to act on a user's behalf, a software agent needs to have a complete understanding of a user's profile, including his/her personal preferences.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This, in turn, may lead to unpredictable privacy issues.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] When users start relying on their software agents more, especially for communication activities, they may lose contact with other human users and look at the world with the eyes of their agents.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] These consequences are what agent researchers and users must consider when dealing with intelligent agent technologies.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] To be more academic, software agent systems are a direct evolution of Multi-Agent Systems (MAS).
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] MAS evolved from Distributed Artificial Intelligence (DAI), Distributed Problem Solving (DPS) and Parallel AI (PAI), thus inheriting all characteristics (good and bad) from DAI and AI.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] John Sculley's 1987 "Knowledge Navigator" video portrayed an image of a relationship between end-users and agents.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Being an ideal first, this field experienced a series of unsuccessful top-down implementations, instead of a piece-by-piece, bottom-up approach.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The range of agent types is now (from 1990) broad: WWW, search engines, etc.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Buyer agents travel around a network (e.g. the internet) retrieving information about goods and services.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] These agents, also known as 'shopping bots', work very efficiently for commodity products such as CDs, books, electronic components, and other one-size-fits-all products.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Buyer agents are typically optimized to allow for digital payment services used in e-commerce and traditional businesses.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] User agents, or personal agents, are intelligent agents that take action on your behalf.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Monitoring and surveillance agents are used to observe and report on equipment, usually computer systems.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The agents may keep track of company inventory levels, observe competitors' prices and relay them back to the company, watch stock manipulation by insider trading and rumors, etc.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] For example, NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory has an agent that monitors inventory, planning, schedules equipment orders to keep costs down, and manages food storage facilities.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] These agents usually monitor complex computer networks that can keep track of the configuration of each computer connected to the network.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] A special case of monitoring-and-surveillance agents are organizations of agents used to automate decision-making process during tactical operations.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The agents monitor the status of assets (ammunition, weapons available, platforms for transport, etc.) and receive goals from higher level agents.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The agents then pursue the goals with the assets at hand, minimizing expenditure of the assets while maximizing goal attainment.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This agent uses information technology to find trends and patterns in an abundance of information from many different sources.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The user can sort through this information in order to find whatever information they are seeking.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] A data mining agent operates in a data warehouse discovering information.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] A 'data warehouse' brings together information from many different sources.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] "Data mining" is the process of looking through the data warehouse to find information that you can use to take action, such as ways to increase sales or keep customers who are considering defecting.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] 'Classification' is one of the most common types of data mining, which finds patterns in information and categorizes them into different classes.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Data mining agents can also detect major shifts in trends or a key indicator and can detect the presence of new information and alert you to it.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] For example, the agent may detect a decline in the construction industry for an economy; based on this relayed information construction companies will be able to make intelligent decisions regarding the hiring/firing of employees or the purchase/lease of equipment in order to best suit their firm.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Some other examples of current intelligent agents include some spam filters, game bots, and server monitoring tools.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Search engine indexing bots also qualify as intelligent agents.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Software bots are becoming important in software engineering.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Agents are also used in software security application to intercept, examine and act on various types of content.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] For software agents to work together efficiently they must share semantics of their data elements.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This can be done by having computer systems publish their metadata.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Agent systems are used to model real-world systems with concurrency or parallel processing.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The agent uses its access methods to go out into local and remote databases to forage for content.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] These access methods may include setting up news stream delivery to the agent, or retrieval from bulletin boards, or using a spider to walk the Web.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The content that is retrieved in this way is probably already partially filtered – by the selection of the newsfeed or the databases that are searched.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The agent next may use its detailed searching or language-processing machinery to extract keywords or signatures from the body of the content that has been received or retrieved.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This abstracted content (or event) is then passed to the agent's Reasoning or inferencing machinery in order to decide what to do with the new content.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This process combines the event content with the rule-based or knowledge content provided by the user.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] If this process finds a good hit or match in the new content, the agent may use another piece of its machinery to do a more detailed search on the content.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Finally, the agent may decide to take an action based on the new content; for example, to notify the user that an important event has occurred.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This action is verified by a security function and then given the authority of the user.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The agent makes use of a user-access method to deliver that message to the user.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] If the user confirms that the event is important by acting quickly on the notification, the agent may also employ its learning machinery to increase its weighting for this kind of event.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Bots can act on behalf of their creators to do good as well as bad.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] There are a few ways which bots can be created to demonstrate that they are designed with the best intention and are not built to do harm.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] This is first done by having a bot identify itself in the user-agent HTTP header when communicating with a site.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] The source IP address must also be validated to establish itself as legitimate.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] Next, the bot must also always respect a site's robots.txt file since it has become the standard across most of the web.
[src:function-calling-llm/software-agent] And like respecting the robots.txt file, bots should shy away from being too aggressive and respect any crawl delay instructions.
